  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to the Poetry Collection of the Shuangming Studio
  author: Lee Inro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In ancient times, Bukshang wrote in his preface to the Book of Poetry: "What lies dormant in the heart becomes loyalty; what emerges in speech becomes poetry." Yang Ziun likewise declared: "Speech is the voice of the heart." The heart, though it spans from heaven to earth, dwells perpetually in stillness and silence, in depths beyond measure, invisible in form. Only through language does it reveal itself; only through poetry does it become manifest. Like metal and stone—soundless things by nature—yet strike them and they sing. Thus the melancholy of Qu Yuan and Song Yu, the serene simplicity of Tao Qian and Xie Tiao, the brilliant elegance of Li Bai and Du Fu—though a thousand years have passed, we read their verses and clearly envision their being, without the slightest blemish obscuring their character. How else might one know the heart and nature of the ancients save through their poetry?

    Our esteemed friend now stands as a teacher to this age, as chief among the hundred officials. Having retired from service to dwell in his native village, he nurtures his spirit and preserves his nature, consorting not with the world, wandering alone through the realm of nothingness. His vital force flows boundless; his heart rests in perfect peace. Thus what emanates from his being and resonates in his poetry is readily understood. He once gathered with the venerable elders at the Shuangming Studio, composing verses to commemorate the occasion. His younger brother, the Grand Preceptor, continued this tradition, crafting words both elegant and refined, bearing the marks of true exemplars. These deserve to be sung in the great tradition and transmitted to posterity, that all may know our friend's extraordinary and timeless cultivation—surpassing even the legendary gathering of the Seven Elders at Bai Juyi's abode. Though my rank and age set me apart, unworthy to stand in their number, I have humbly followed in their wake, privileged to receive their words and teachings. Thus I have gathered these poems and written this preface. All who contributed verses are listed herein, whether or not they attended the gathering. Respectfully submitted.
  footnotes:
    - Bukshang (卜商) was a disciple of Confucius; the sentiment quoted reflects the classical understanding that poetry expresses the inner moral character.
    - The Shuangming Studio (雙明齋) was the gathering place where the esteemed official and his circle of elder scholars composed poetry together.
    - The Seven Elders gathering refers to a famous meeting of aged poets and officials in Chinese literary tradition, referenced here to suggest the significance of the Shuangming Studio circle.
